Support of JavascriptMVC EJS tags <%== and <%#

EJS parser in JavascriptMVC supports some special tags.
This commit adds supports for some of these.

 - for raw (unescaped) output you can use tag <%== output %>
   (for extracting strings it treats the same as <%= output %>)

 - adding comments with tag <%# Comment %>
   (for extracting strings it treats the same as the include statement:
   removes from temporary js content)

See: http://javascriptmvc.com/docs/can.EJS.html#section_MagicTags

Fixes #59.

Added `po-headers` option that can be used to override the default headers.

Example: 

    options["po-headers"] = {
      "project-id-version": "MyProject 1.0",
      "language-team": "MyTeam <team@my.org>",
      "language": "en_US"
    }

Also added a test for custom headers.

Problem to solve:
When jsxgettext is used in an automatic workflow for extracting strings (for instance with grunt-jsxgettext) without the `join-existing` option, the generated .pot file will always contain the default headers.

Since there can be a workflow where the freshly generated .pot file is later merged with .po files, we might want to set project, version and team information already in the .pot file to prevent other tools like poEdit from complaining about missing information.

That's where the `po-headers` option can be used (for instance in the grunt-jsxgettext configuration file).

Add `sort` option for sorted strings in output file

Adds a `sort` option (shorthand `-s`) to allow people to get sorted
strings in the resultant file. Sorting makes the `po/pot` files
easier to follow with version control, preventing arbitrary moving of
unchanged strings in the file. It also makes debugging easier.

Use pug instead of jade

The jade module was discontinued and had some `npm audit` warnings.

This replaces jade with pug and updates the jade parser based
on the updated AST format.

with the source.

@tagoh explains the reason as:
>Sure. basically there are no different between a header which contains the project id, the targeted language, the content type and so on, and other translations in its format. even though the header are put as the empty msgid, it is still referrable with "" unless it is flagged as fuzzy. so the original getttext to generate a POT file behaves to add a fuzzy flag to avoid such sutiation as a workaround of the defect of the format.
>Oh, and inherits flags on the header to POs as well. translators and all of the web translation platforms doesn't touch it.
